Short Circuit 
___________________

Operators stop comparisons as soon as a value is determined â€” meaning it may end early if it already knows the result.

var age = 21 
var gender = 'female'; 

age < 22 && gender === 'female' 		// Has to look at both sides of the
									// logical && (and) operator

age > 22 && gender === 'male'		//
Will not even look at the 
// second half, because the first 
// half already caused the boolean 
// expression to fail

TRUTHY VS FALSY 
______________________

FALSY VALUES 
_____
Here are some values that evaluate to false:
false
0 (the number zero)
"" (an empty string)
null
undefined

TERNARY OPERATORS 
______________________
Syntax Description:
condition ? value if true : value if false

 Example:
var age = 12;
(age < 18) ? 'child': 'adult';
  'child'


SWITCH OPERATOR
____________________
 Switch statements compares expressions to a sewries of cases and executes block of code once match is found 
 
switch (expression) {
  case value1:
    // Code block if expression matches value1
    break;
  case value2:
    // Code block if expression matches value2
    break;
  ...
  
  switch (dayOfTheWeek) {
  case 'Monday':
    console.log('Have a great start to the week!');
    break;
  case 'Tuesday':
    console.log('Have a good Tuesday :)');
    break;
  case 'Wednesday':
    console.log('You are halfway there!');
    break;
  case 'Thursday':
    console.log('One more day until the weekend.');
    break;
  case 'Friday':
    console.log('Happy Friday, have a good weekend!');
    break;
  default:
    console.log('Not a weekday!');
}

